ðŸ¦– Dino Run â€“ FPGA-Based Real-Time Game

Dino Run is a real-time, VGA-rendered game implemented in SystemVerilog and deployed on the Basys3 FPGA Board. This project highlights expertise 
in digital design, finite state machines (FSMs), and hardware-software integration.

ðŸ“Œ Overview
	â€¢ Designed and implemented a hardware-accelerated game inspired by the classic Dino Run.
	â€¢ Utilized finite state machines to manage gameplay states such as title screen, running, collision, and reset.
	â€¢ Rendered game visuals (dino, obstacles, score) in real-time using VGA output.
	â€¢ Integrated hardware controls via Basys3 pushbuttons for user interaction (jump, duck, reset).

ðŸ› ï¸ Key Contributions
	1.Finite State Machine (FSM) Design
		â€¢ Implemented a modular FSM for game state transitions, ensuring smooth gameplay flow.
		â€¢ States included TITLE_SCREEN, RUNNING, COLLISION, and RESET.
	2. Random Obstacle Generation
		â€¢ Developed a 16-bit Linear Feedback Shift Register (LFSR) to pseudo-randomly spawn obstacles with varying attributes (height, type).
	3. VGA Graphics Rendering
		â€¢ Designed a VGA timing generator to synchronize the display at 640x480 resolution.
		â€¢ Rendered animated sprites (dino, obstacles, ground) and a dynamic score counter.
	4. Hardware Integration
		â€¢ Programmed the Basys3 FPGA to handle user inputs for gameplay via pushbuttons.
		â€¢ Incorporated a 7-segment display driver for real-time score display.
	5. Verification and Deployment
		â€¢ Verified module functionality using comprehensive SystemVerilog testbenches.
		â€¢ Synthesized the design and programmed it onto the Basys3 FPGA for demonstration.

